\begin{tabular}{r||c|c|c|c|c|c}
  System          & $X$   & ${\widehat X}$ & metrics     & $\alpha,\beta$& Section& Ref\\ \hline
  Canonical pair  &${\mathbb R}$  & ${\mathbb R}$ & abs         & all           &&  \cite{BLW2}  \\
  Mechanics       &${\mathbb R}^n$& ${\mathbb R}^n$ & Euclidean & 1,2           &\ref{sec:exStandard}            \\ \hline
  angle/number    & ${\mathbb T}$&       & arc or chordal  & 2         &&  \cite{KW} \\
                          &&${\mathbb Z}$   &discrete or abs &  1,2     &\ref{sec:exNumber}&\\    \hline
  qudit           &${\mathbb Z}_d$&${\mathbb Z}_d$& discrete     & 1            &\ref{sec:exQudit}&\\
  qubit string    &${\mathbb Z}_2^N$&${\mathbb Z}_2^N$& Hamming& all            &\ref{sec:exStrings}&
\end{tabular}
 \caption{\label{tab:choose}Phase spaces and parameters considered in this paper}
\end{centering}\end{table}


The paper is organized as follows: We will review the basic theory of phase space quantum mechanics in the next section, and the relevant notions of uncertainty in Sect.~\ref{sec:unc}. This is followed in Sect.\ref{sec:examp} by discussing the special instances, as summarized in Table~\ref{tab:choose}.

\section{Phase spaces}\label{sec:ps}
In this chapter we outline phase space quantum mechanics in the general setting outlined above. The generality forces us to use a relatively abstract (i.e., mathematical) language. Physicists feeling not so comfortable with this level of abstraction should read this section and the next with two concrete examples from Table~\ref{tab:choose} in mind, one of which should be the ``standard'' case of one position/momentum pair.

The origin of the theory outlined here is in \cite{QHA,QHAcorr}, where it is carried out for the standard phase spaces ${\mathbb R}^n\times{\mathbb R}^n$. The generalization to general phase spaces is straightforward for the parts we need for the current context, and only needs some standard results of the harmonic analysis (Fourier theory) of locally compact abelian groups \cite{Reiter,Hewitt}. A detailed treatment, also of the fine points, is in preparation with Jussi Schultz.

We assume from on now that a group $X$ of ``position shifts'' is given. Technically, any locally compact abelian group is allowed, but in physical or QI applications we will be talking about one of the groups from Table~1. Apart from one or more canonical degrees of freedom, like position/momentum of quantum optical field quadratures, we may also have angle or phase variables with an intrinsic periodicity given by the group ${\mathbb T}$ of phases (complex numbers with modulus $1$ under multiplication) or, equivalently ${\mathbb T}={\mathbb R}/(2\pi{\mathbb Z})$. Further there may be discrete variables given by integers and either unbounded ($X={\mathbb Z}$) or modulo some number $d$ ($X={\mathbb Z}_d$). Furthermore, arbitrary combinations of these choices are allowed.

We will denote integration with respect to the Haar measure on $X$ by ``$\int\!dx$''. This measure is unique up to a constant, and is characterized by its translation invariance, i.e., by the possibility to substitute a shifted variable without functional determinant factors. In the discrete cases it is often natural to give each point unit measure. Integrals with respect to this ``counting measure'' are just sums over $x$. In the compact cases (${\mathbb T}$ and ${\mathbb Z}_d$ and their products) the total Haar measure is finite, and it is often convenient to take it as a probability measure, i.e., normalized to $1$. Note that these natural choices are in conflict for ${\mathbb Z}_d$, which means that we have to make choices very much analogous to where one wants to stick the normalization factors $2\pi$ for the standard Fourier transform.

The basic Hilbert space of our systems will now be ${\mathcal H}={\mathcal L}^2(X,dx)$, the square integrable functions on $X$. In it the projection valued position observable acts by multiplication operators, i.e., the position probability density associated with a vector $\psi$ will be ${\vert{\psi(x)}\vert}^2$.  The unitary shift operators $(U_x\psi)(y)=\psi(y-x)$ are clearly not functions of position. But since the underlying group $X$ is abelian, they commute and can therefore by jointly diagonalized, i.e., be represented as multiplication operators in another representation. This will, of course, be the momentum representation reached by the Fourier transform. The Fourier transform of a function $\psi:X\to{\mathbb C}$ will be a function ${\mathcal F}\psi:{\widehat X}\to{\mathbb C}$, where ${\widehat X}$ is the dual group of $X$. This is abstractly the set of continuous multiplicative functions from $X$ to ${\mathbb T}$. If $p\in{\widehat X}$ labels such a function, we write it as $x\mapsto{\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylep$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylex$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}$. By definition,  ${\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylep$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle{x_1+x_2}$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}={\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylep$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle{x_1}$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}{\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylep$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle{x_2}$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}$. The sum in ${\widehat X}$ is defined by ${\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle{p_1+p_2}$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylex$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}={\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle{p_1}$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylex$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}{\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle{p_2}$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylex$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}$. Concretely, when
$X={\mathbb R}^n$ we also have ${\widehat X}={\mathbb R}^n$ and ${\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylep$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylex$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}=\exp(ip\cdot x)$, where the dot denotes the scalar product. Similarly, for the pair $\Xi={\mathbb T}\times{\mathbb Z}$ we have
${\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle\alpha$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylen$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}=\exp(i\alpha n)$. Note that changing $\alpha$ here to $\alpha+2\pi$ (which represents the same element in ${\mathbb T}$) does not change the value of ${\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstyle\alpha$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylen$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}$, and this property is what forces $n\in{\mathbb Z}$. The same reasoning leads to the form ${\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\lfloor$}\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylep$}\vert\raisebox{4pt}{$\scriptstylex$}\raisebox{3pt}{$\scriptstyle\rfloor$}}=\exp(2\pi i px/d)$ for $\Xi={\mathbb Z}_d\times{\mathbb Z}_d$. Now the Fourier transform and its inverse are defined by

